# Enter your code here!

m <- mean(mtcars$mpg)
v <- var(mtcars$mpg)

  1. Create two tables to summarize 1) average mpg for each cylinder class and 2) the standard deviation of mpg for each gear class.
# Enter your code here!

average_mpg_by_cyl <- aggregate(mpg ~ cyl, data = mtcars, FUN = mean)

sd_mpg_by_gear <- aggregate(mpg ~ gear, data = mtcars, FUN = sd)
  1. Create a crosstab that shows the number of observations belong to each cylinder and gear class combinations. The table should show how many observations given the car has 4 cylinders with 3 gears, 4 cylinders with 4 gears, etc. Report which combination is recorded in this data set and how many observations for this type of car.
# Enter your code here!
cyl_gear_crosstab <- table(mtcars$cyl, mtcars$gear)

print("Crosstab of Cylinder and Gear Combinations:")
## [1] "Crosstab of Cylinder and Gear Combinations:"
print(cyl_gear_crosstab)
##    
##      3  4  5
##   4  1  8  2
##   6  2  4  1
##   8 12  0  2
max_count <- max(cyl_gear_crosstab)
most_common_combination <- which(cyl_gear_crosstab == max_count, arr.ind = TRUE)

most_common_cyl <- rownames(cyl_gear_crosstab)[most_common_combination[, "row"]]
most_common_gear <- colnames(cyl_gear_crosstab)[most_common_combination[, "col"]]

# Print the statement

# Head of the cleaned data set
head(housingData)
# Enter your code here!
neighborhood_stats <- by(housingData, housingData$Neighborhood, function(sub_data) {
  c(
    Mean_Value_per_SqFt = mean(sub_data$Market.Value.per.SqFt, na.rm = TRUE),
    Median_Value_per_SqFt = median(sub_data$Market.Value.per.SqFt, na.rm = TRUE),
    Range_Value_per_SqFt = diff(range(sub_data$Market.Value.per.SqFt, na.rm = TRUE)),
    Average_Year_Built = mean(sub_data$Year.Built, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
})
